objects.name: UNC1069 Crypto-Targeting

objects.content:

AI video deepfakes for social engineering, fake Zoom meetings, ClickFix (malicious troubleshooting commands), deployment of SILENCELIFT and DEEPBREATH malware.

objects.name: SolarWinds WHD Exploitation with Virtualization Persistence
objects.description:
Threat actors are exploiting SolarWinds Web Help Desk to deploy hidden QEMU virtual machines under the SYSTEM account, creating a 'ghost' SSH tunnel for persistent access.

Analysis:
The use of QEMU for persistence is a highly sophisticated 'Living-off-the-Land' tactic designed to bypass traditional EDR and monitoring tools by encapsulating malicious traffic within a virtualized container.

Recommendations:
- Update SolarWinds WHD to version 2026.1 immediately.
- Hunt for unauthorized instances of QEMU or Zoho Assist processes (ToolsIQ.exe).

objects.content: The cyber threat landscape for February 10, 2026, is dominated by high-intensity state-sponsored operations and sophisticated ransomware tactics. Chinese threat actors (UNC3886, Amaranth-Dragon, Storm 15-16) are aggressively targeting critical infrastructure in Singapore and Southeast Asia, while also engaging in information warfare against European defense interests. Concurrently, North Korean actor UNC1069 has integrated Generative AI (Deepfakes) into social engineering campaigns against the cryptocurrency sector. From a technical standpoint, 'Living-off-the-Land' (LotL) techniques have evolved, with attackers using legitimate virtualization software (QEMU) and RMM tools (Zoho ManageEngine) to hide malicious activity. Critical vulnerabilities in remote management and enterprise software (BeyondTrust, SolarWinds, Fortinet, SAP) remain primary entry vectors, necessitating urgent patching.
